<ArticleLayout
  title="Garage Storage Tubs: What to Sort Before Buying More Containers"
  description="Before buying more garage storage tubs, sort what you own, check tub size, shelf depth, lid fit, stack height, weight, moisture, pests and what should not be stored in ordinary containers."
  category="Garage Storage"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/garage.webp"
  imageAlt="An organised garage with wall storage, shelves and clear floor space"
>
  <p>
    Garage storage tubs can be useful, but they can also hide the real problem. A neat stack
    of tubs may still contain broken tools, old paint, outgrown sports gear, tangled cords,
    damp towels, missing parts and items nobody has used for years.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying more containers, it is worth sorting what is already in the garage. The
    goal is not to put every loose item into a tub. The goal is to choose containers that
    suit the items, the shelf space, the garage conditions and the way the household
    actually uses the garage.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to sort and check before buying more garage storage tubs, bins,
    boxes or labelled containers.
  </p>

  <h2>Start by sorting before buying</h2>
  <p>
    Storage tubs are often bought too early.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you buy containers before sorting, you may end up paying to store things that should
    have been removed, donated, recycled, repaired, disposed of appropriately or moved
    somewhere else.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying tubs, sort garage items into broad groups:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>tools and hardware</li>
    <li>sports gear</li>
    <li>camping gear</li>
    <li>beach gear</li>
    <li>seasonal decorations</li>
    <li>car cleaning products</li>
    <li>gardening items</li>
    <li>pet supplies</li>
    <li>spare household items</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>painting and renovation leftovers</li>
    <li>cables, cords and small parts</li>
    <li>items that belong inside the home</li>
    <li>items that should leave the garage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This step shows what type of container is actually needed. Some items suit clear lidded
    tubs. Some need open bins. Some need shelves. Some need cabinets. Some should not be
    stored in ordinary tubs at all.
  </p>

  <h2>Remove what should not be stored</h2>
  <p>
    Garage tubs can make clutter look controlled without reducing it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying more containers, check for items that do not need a permanent place.
  </p>
  <p>Look for:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Item type</th>
        <th>Common examples</th>
        <th>Better action</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Broken items</td>
        <td>cracked tubs, damaged tools, broken sports gear</td>
        <td>repair or dispose of appropriately</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Duplicates</td>
        <td>repeated cords, tools, containers, fittings</td>
        <td>keep the useful set and remove extras</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Outgrown items</td>
        <td>helmets, pads, shoes, toys, pet gear</td>
        <td>donate, sell, recycle or remove if suitable</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Mystery items</td>
        <td>unknown parts, loose fixings, old accessories</td>
        <td>match up or remove</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Expired or questionable products</td>
        <td>old chemicals, paints, adhesives, pesticides</td>
        <td>follow label or local disposal guidance</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Moisture-damaged items</td>
        <td>damp cardboard, mouldy fabric, rusted items</td>
        <td>assess carefully before storing again</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    If an item has not been used, recognised or needed for years, a new tub may not be the
    answer.
  </p>

  <h2>Group items by use, not just type</h2>
  <p>
    A common mistake is grouping items by broad type only.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, "sports gear" may include a soccer ball used every week, beach bats used
    twice a year and an outgrown helmet that should not be kept. Putting all of that into
    one large tub may make access worse.
  </p>
  <p>Instead, group items by use:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>used weekly</li>
    <li>used monthly</li>
    <li>used seasonally</li>
    <li>used rarely but worth keeping</li>
    <li>heavy</li>
    <li>fragile</li>
    <li>dirty or outdoor use</li>
    <li>hazardous or sensitive</li>
    <li>needs child or pet control</li>
    <li>should not be stored in the garage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This helps you decide whether an item needs an open bin, a labelled tub, a shelf zone, a
    cabinet, a toolbox, or no garage storage at all.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure shelves before buying tubs</h2>
  <p>
    Tubs and shelves need to work together.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying containers, measure the actual storage space where they will sit.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shelf width</li>
    <li>shelf depth</li>
    <li>shelf height</li>
    <li>clearance between shelves</li>
    <li>whether lids add extra height</li>
    <li>whether handles add extra width</li>
    <li>how many tubs fit per shelf</li>
    <li>whether tubs can slide in and out easily</li>
    <li>whether labels remain visible</li>
    <li>whether the shelf load rating suits the filled tubs</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Many garages end up with tubs that almost fit. They overhang the shelf, scrape the shelf
    above, hide labels, or become too heavy to move once filled.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure first, then choose tub sizes.
  </p>

  <h2>Check tub depth against garage clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Large tubs can create the same problem as deep shelves. They take up floor space and can
    block movement.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying large containers, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether they will sit on shelves or the floor</li>
    <li>whether they will block the car door</li>
    <li>whether they will narrow the walking path</li>
    <li>whether they will interfere with bikes, bins or tools</li>
    <li>whether they will sit near the garage door track</li>
    <li>whether they can be lifted and carried without awkward strain</li>
    <li>whether they will be dragged across the floor</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A large tub may hold more, but it may also become too heavy or awkward to use.
  </p>
  <p>
    In many garages, medium tubs are more practical than very large tubs because they are
    easier to lift, label, stack and fit on shelves.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose clear, opaque or open containers deliberately</h2>
  <p>
    Different container types suit different uses.
  </p>
  <p>
    Clear tubs can make contents easier to identify, but they can look visually messy if
    everything is visible. Opaque tubs can look neater, but they rely more heavily on
    labels. Open bins are easy to access, but they do not protect contents from dust, pests
    or moisture.
  </p>
  <p>Use the container type to match the job.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Container type</th>
        <th>Works well for</th>
        <th>Check before buying</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Clear lidded tubs</td>
        <td>seasonal gear, grouped household items, visible contents</td>
        <td>lid fit, stackability, plastic quality, shelf fit</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Opaque lidded tubs</td>
        <td>labelled categories, visual tidiness</td>
        <td>clear labels, consistent sizes, lid security</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Open bins</td>
        <td>balls, frequently used gear, quick-return items</td>
        <td>dust, pests, access, stability</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Small divided boxes</td>
        <td>screws, fixings, accessories, small parts</td>
        <td>divider strength, label space, portability</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Heavy-duty tubs</td>
        <td>heavier or awkward items</td>
        <td>load guidance, lifting weight, shelf rating</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shallow trays</td>
        <td>tools, cords, small project items</td>
        <td>shelf fit, visibility, containment</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Do not use one container type for everything. Garages usually need a mix.
  </p>

  <h2>Check lids properly</h2>
  <p>
    The lid is not a minor detail.
  </p>
  <p>
    A poor lid can make tubs frustrating, especially in garages where dust, pests or
    moisture are concerns.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the lid clips or simply rests on top</li>
    <li>whether the lid stays fitted when stacked</li>
    <li>whether the lid is easy to remove</li>
    <li>whether replacement lids are likely to be available</li>
    <li>whether the lid adds extra height</li>
    <li>whether labels can be placed on the lid or front</li>
    <li>whether the lid suits the contents</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some tubs are stackable only when the lids are fitted correctly. Others may flex or
    become unstable when overloaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check the product's stacking and load guidance rather than assuming all lidded tubs can
    be stacked reliably.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid making tubs too heavy</h2>
  <p>
    The larger the tub, the easier it is to overload.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before filling a tub, think about whether it can be lifted, carried and returned by the
    person who will use it.
  </p>
  <p>Heavy tub contents may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>tools</li>
    <li>hardware</li>
    <li>books or paperwork</li>
    <li>paint tins</li>
    <li>car products</li>
    <li>camping equipment</li>
    <li>tiles, fittings or renovation leftovers</li>
    <li>bulk household supplies</li>
    <li>small appliances</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If a tub becomes too heavy, it may sit permanently on the floor, block access or become
    awkward to lift.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep heavy items in smaller tubs or on lower shelves where appropriate. Check both the
    tub guidance and shelf load rating.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with stacking</h2>
  <p>
    Stacked tubs can save space, but they can also become unstable, too heavy or difficult
    to access.
  </p>
  <p>Before stacking tubs, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>manufacturer stacking guidance</li>
    <li>whether the lids lock or nest</li>
    <li>whether the lower tub can handle the weight</li>
    <li>whether the floor or shelf is level</li>
    <li>whether the stack blocks access</li>
    <li>whether the upper tubs are light enough to lift</li>
    <li>whether children or pets may pull at the stack</li>
    <li>whether the stack is near a car, door or walkway</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid stacking heavy tubs high. Avoid stacks that lean, wobble or need to be moved every
    time you want the bottom tub.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you often need the contents, stacking may be the wrong approach.
  </p>

  <h2>Label tubs where they are seen</h2>
  <p>
    Labels only work if they can be read in the real storage position.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying or filling tubs, decide where the label will go.
  </p>
  <p>Good labels should be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>visible from the front</li>
    <li>specific enough to be useful</li>
    <li>easy to update</li>
    <li>readable in garage lighting</li>
    <li>consistent across similar tubs</li>
    <li>not only placed on the lid if tubs are stacked</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid vague labels such as "miscellaneous", "garage stuff" or "random". These usually
    become long-term clutter zones.
  </p>
  <p>Better labels include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Christmas lights</li>
    <li>beach towels and goggles</li>
    <li>camping cooking gear</li>
    <li>car cleaning cloths</li>
    <li>bike helmets and pads</li>
    <li>spare extension cords</li>
    <li>picture hanging hardware</li>
    <li>pet travel gear</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A label should help someone find and return the item without opening every tub.
  </p>

  <h2>Use smaller containers inside larger tubs</h2>
  <p>
    Large tubs can become messy when small items are loose inside them.
  </p>
  <p>
    For categories with small parts, use smaller containers within the tub.
  </p>
  <p>This may suit:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>screws and fixings</li>
    <li>camping accessories</li>
    <li>bike accessories</li>
    <li>sports accessories</li>
    <li>spare cords</li>
    <li>pet accessories</li>
    <li>painting tools</li>
    <li>craft or repair items</li>
    <li>small hardware</li>
    <li>Christmas hooks and clips</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A large tub works best when it holds a clear category, not a jumble of unrelated small
    items.
  </p>

  <h2>Think carefully about moisture</h2>
  <p>
    Garages can be damp, dusty or exposed to water entry. A sealed-looking tub does not
    automatically solve moisture problems.
  </p>
  <p>Before storing items in tubs, check whether the garage has:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>water entering under the door</li>
    <li>damp corners</li>
    <li>condensation</li>
    <li>mould-prone areas</li>
    <li>poor airflow</li>
    <li>wet gear being stored before drying</li>
    <li>items that were already damp</li>
    <li>direct heat or sun exposure</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Closed tubs can protect contents from dust, but they can also trap moisture if damp
    items are placed inside. Wet towels, sports pads, beach gear, muddy shoes and damp
    camping items should be dried before long-term storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing valuable, delicate or moisture-sensitive items in a garage that is not
    suitable for them.
  </p>

  <h2>Watch for pests</h2>
  <p>
    Tubs can help keep items contained, but they do not guarantee pest protection.
  </p>
  <p>Before storing items long term, check for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>gaps around the garage door</li>
    <li>pest activity</li>
    <li>food residue</li>
    <li>pet food or treats</li>
    <li>cardboard boxes</li>
    <li>fabric items</li>
    <li>soft nesting material</li>
    <li>damp areas</li>
    <li>hidden corners behind shelves</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid storing food, pet treats or pest-attracting items casually in ordinary garage
    tubs. If pest activity is present, deal with the underlying issue rather than relying
    only on containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Use appropriate storage and seek pest-control advice where needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Do not put everything hazardous into ordinary tubs</h2>
  <p>
    Some items need more care than a general storage container.
  </p>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>cleaning chemicals</li>
    <li>pesticides</li>
    <li>fuels</li>
    <li>oils</li>
    <li>solvents</li>
    <li>paints</li>
    <li>adhesives</li>
    <li>batteries</li>
    <li>sharp tools</li>
    <li>blades</li>
    <li>power-tool accessories</li>
    <li>pool chemicals</li>
    <li>car products</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Check product labels and manufacturer storage instructions. Keep incompatible products
    separated where required. Keep hazardous products away from children and pets.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing chemicals above head height or where a leak could damage other items. Do
    not rely on an ordinary plastic tub as the solution for hazardous products.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide what should stay out of tubs</h2>
  <p>
    Not every garage item belongs in a container.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some items may be better on shelves, hooks, racks, cabinets or floor zones.
  </p>
  <p>Examples include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>bikes</li>
    <li>scooters</li>
    <li>ladders</li>
    <li>long garden tools</li>
    <li>frequently used balls</li>
    <li>dirty shoes</li>
    <li>wet sports gear</li>
    <li>power tools in cases</li>
    <li>sharp tools needing controlled storage</li>
    <li>chemicals needing label-based storage</li>
    <li>heavy items that are awkward to lift</li>
    <li>items used every day</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Tubs are useful for grouping and protecting items, but they are not the best answer for
    every garage problem.
  </p>

  <h2>Common garage tub mistakes</h2>
  <p>Avoid these mistakes before buying:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying tubs before sorting the garage</li>
    <li>choosing tubs that do not fit the shelf depth</li>
    <li>stacking heavy tubs too high</li>
    <li>using vague labels</li>
    <li>placing labels only on lids</li>
    <li>storing wet gear in closed tubs</li>
    <li>using large tubs for tiny mixed items</li>
    <li>putting chemicals into ordinary tubs without checking labels</li>
    <li>storing heavy items in oversized tubs</li>
    <li>choosing tubs that block the walking path</li>
    <li>buying too many different sizes</li>
    <li>hiding items that should be removed</li>
    <li>storing moisture-sensitive items in a damp garage</li>
    <li>assuming lidded tubs are pest-proof</li>
    <li>filling every tub immediately</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A garage full of matching tubs can still be poorly organised if the categories are
    wrong.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple garage tub checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying more containers, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>what categories actually need tubs</li>
    <li>what should be removed first</li>
    <li>what is used weekly</li>
    <li>what is seasonal</li>
    <li>what is heavy</li>
    <li>what is damp, dirty or odorous</li>
    <li>what is hazardous or sensitive</li>
    <li>what should not be stored in a tub</li>
    <li>shelf width, depth and height</li>
    <li>existing tub measurements</li>
    <li>shelf load ratings</li>
    <li>likely filled tub weight</li>
    <li>label position</li>
    <li>whether clear or opaque tubs are better</li>
    <li>whether open bins are more useful</li>
    <li>whether the garage has moisture or pest issues</li>
    <li>whether the tubs will block access</li>
    <li>whether children or pets can access the contents</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these notes before shopping. They will usually prevent buying the wrong container
    size or too many containers.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Garage tubs should be bought after sorting, not before.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start by removing what should not be stored. Group what remains by use, weight, risk and
    access. Then measure shelves, check tub size, choose labels carefully and avoid
    overloading containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    For many households, the best solution is not more tubs. It is fewer categories, clearer
    labels, better shelf fit and more care with heavy, damp, hazardous or frequently used
    items.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good garage tub system should make items easier to find and return. If the containers
    hide clutter, trap moisture, become too heavy or block access, they are not solving the
    real garage storage problem.
  </p>

